from the turret of an abrams tank in michigan 
to a union hall in republican orange county calif michael 
dukakis fought all last week to regain the initiative in the 
presidential race 
it was really a good week he told reporters on the long 
flight saturday night from california to the nations capital 
a good week had been a long time coming 
aides to the democratic presidential candidate readily conceded 
the race had changed dramatically during the past month with 
george bush enjoying a surge 
gone were those doubledigit leads dukakis once held in national 
polls gone also was the sense some had had that he was a near 
certain bet to win back the white house for the democrats 
presidential campaigns can turn on which candidate is more 
successful at setting the issues agenda and defining the public 
perception of the contenders 
for the past month voters have learned more about dukakis from 
republican bush and his allies than they did from the democratic 
candidate 
they have received a picture of a northeast liberal who vetoed 
legislation to require recitation of the pledge of allegiance in 
public schools of a governor who supported allowing convicts to 
have weekend furloughs from prison of someone who opposed most 
major weapons systems 
the past week dukakis set out to alter that image to sharpen 
the message as his aides put it 
he sought to counter the charge that he is weak on defense by 
riding in the turret of a tank and by delivering a speech decidedly 
hawkish for dukakis in tone 
the emphasis in his speech at georgetown university was on the 
weapons systems he favors the trident ii the stealth bomber a 
new fighter and a new attack submarine 
then he flew to california where the emphasis was on fighting 
crime and drugs as well as on the environment 
his speeches contained more specifics doubling the number of 
drug enforcement agents and elevating the environmental protection 
agency to cabinet status 
it was clear the dukakis campaign had decided it was time to 
make clear what he stands for 
in most of the country voters dont know who mike dukakis 
is said francis obrien a senior campaign adviser 
no one summed that up better than george bush the week before 
the republican national convention when he dubbed dukakis the 
stealth candidate a reference to the experimental plane 
designed to evade radar detection 
it was a jibe at a candidate who had avoided laying out specific 
proposals on many major questions and had directed his party to 
come up with a nonspecific platform 
for those who saw democrats unduly burdened by past promises to 
a variety of interest groups dukakis strategy seemed right 
but as the fall campaign opened it gave the republicans an 
opportunity to be the first to give voters a picture of dukakis 
suddenly the talk within the dukakis campaign was of the need 
for a good solid message 
it would have been better had he spoken up a little more 
sharply a little sooner said tony podesta who is running the 
dukakis campaign in california 
the republican attacks were relentless and at most stops dukakis 
found himself pressed to respond he often resisted reluctant to 
get into extended negative campaigning 
but he couldnt remain silent 
we cant let them we cant let bush and his aides lay charges 
on us that we dont answer said obrien 
while he sometimes appeared reluctant to respond to the vice 
president dukakis was not shy about going on the attack 
he repeatedly linked bush to manuel noriega whom dukakis always 
describes as the drugpeddling panamanian dictator and said the 
vice president had provided zero protection for the environment 
dukakis sense that he was having a good week was helped by the 
reports of rhetorical gaffes by bush and his running mate dan 
quayle 
dan quayle doesnt know what century hes in and george bush 
cant remember the pledge of allegiance he told a delighted 
partisan crowd in california 
